I’ve spent my life alone—no siblings, no shared laughter, no one to argue with or compete against. My birthday wasn’t a party. It was just me, a candle, and silence. I’d sit in the kitchen, eating alone, watching the sun go down, and for the first time, I realized I didn’t need anyone to feel complete. (That’s when I learned self-reliance wasn’t a choice—it was a necessity.) I didn’t grow up with cousins or friends to share secrets with. (My only connection was with my parents, and even that was strained by the weight of what I was expected to carry.) I learned early that every decision—what to study, where to go, how to speak—was mine to make. (I didn’t have to ask permission. I just had to *do* it.) I’d sit with my father at night, and he’d say, “You’re the only one. You have to carry everything.” (And I did. I carried the expectations, the pressure, the silence.) I didn’t know then that being an only child meant I’d never learn how to share pain. (I learned to carry it alone—like a stone in my chest, heavy and unspoken.) Now I know: it shaped me. It taught me to stand when others fall. It made me strong not because I was taught to be, but because I had to be. (And in that solitude, I found my own voice—quiet, steady, unshakable.)  

{I didn’t need to prove myself to anyone. I just had to prove I could stand.}  
[Being the only one meant I had no one to blame when things went wrong.]  
(And when I finally saw Belle—her eyes calm, her strength quiet—I knew: I didn’t need to win her with force. I just needed to stand.)  
{That’s how I learned to love without needing to be seen.}  
[It wasn’t about being loved. It was about being *true*.]
